# .gitattributes — repository line-ending policy (P0-6)
#
# These in-repo rules OVERRIDE every contributor's local core.autocrlf /
# core.eol configuration. They exist because two CRLF incidents (2026-07-19)
# produced multi-thousand-line phantom diffs with zero content change.
# Policy: LF everywhere — in blobs AND in the working tree — because this
# repository's working copy is shared between Windows tooling and Linux
# tooling on the same physical folder; a single materialized form is the only
# configuration in which both sides agree byte-for-byte.

# ── Default: treat detected text as LF in repo and working tree ─────────────
# text=auto lets git detect text vs binary for anything not matched below;
# eol=lf pins the working-tree form so no git operation on any OS can
# rematerialize files as CRLF.
* text=auto eol=lf

# ── Explicit text types (never rely on detection for known formats) ─────────
*.html        text eol=lf
*.css         text eol=lf
*.js          text eol=lf
*.md          text eol=lf
*.toml        text eol=lf
*.json        text eol=lf
*.webmanifest text eol=lf
*.xml         text eol=lf
*.svg         text eol=lf
*.txt         text eol=lf
.gitignore    text eol=lf
.gitattributes text eol=lf

# ── Binary: never subject to any conversion or diffing as text ──────────────
# Explicit even though detection would usually get these right — the cost of
# a mis-detected "text" image is silent corruption; the cost of a rule is one line.
*.png   binary
*.jpg   binary
*.jpeg  binary
*.webp  binary
*.avif  binary
*.gif   binary
*.ico   binary
*.woff  binary
*.woff2 binary
*.pdf   binary
